<paragraph blockId="87.[212,1172,1594,1683]" pageId="87" pageNumber="193">
Two gravid females had 
<specimenCount box="[488,575,1594,1619]" pageId="87" pageNumber="193" type="egg">six eggs</specimenCount>
and one had 
<specimenCount box="[727,812,1594,1619]" pageId="87" pageNumber="193" type="egg">12 eggs</specimenCount>
. In one of those with six mature eggs they measured 0.58 × 
<quantity box="[512,613,1626,1650]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="87" pageNumber="193" unit="mm" value="0.29">0.29 mm</quantity>
; but in the fly with 12 mature eggs they measured only 0.46 × 
<quantity box="[343,445,1658,1682]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="87" pageNumber="193" unit="mm" value="0.2">0.20 mm</quantity>
. Otherwise the eggs resemble 
<figureCitation box="[779,909,1658,1682]" captionStart="Figure 35" captionStartId="52.[144,211,1413,1435]" captionTargetBox="[155,1103,173,1379]" captionTargetId="figure-59@52.[144,1104,173,1381]" captionTargetPageId="52" captionText="Figure 35. Megaselia halterata. (A) Female abdominal tergites 5–7. (B) Egg, with anterior end facing top of page. (C) Left face of male hypopygium. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5207014" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5207014/files/figure.png" pageId="87" pageNumber="193">Figure 35B</figureCitation>
